Lab 4: Probability distributions



Today’s investigation. Biologists are interested in understanding patterns in life and how specific factors shape those patterns. However, it takes more than interest to advance our understanding; it takes estimation with uncertainty. That is, we need to make the best out of the sample under study in order to approximate the true population value or parameter of interest. Parameters are fixed values but our estimates from random samples are variables and thus are charactetrized by a probability distribution. Today, we will learn how to estimate a sample statistic from random samples and measure the uncertainty - precision - around such statistic using a dataset of rhesus macaques from CSULB Quantitative Ecology Lab.

Introduction

In this lab we will estimate sample statistics from probability distributions to approximate true population parameters. For this, we will explore the distribution of age at death in Cayo Santiago rhesus macaques during major hurricanes (Fig. 1). Cayo Santiago is one of the world’s oldest monkey colonies where rhesus macaques free range from birth to death. As a research field station, Cayo Santiago monkeys are all uniquely identied allowing for demographic data collection. Thus, the Cayo Santiago rhesus macaque population presents unique oportunities to address ecological drivers shaping survival and reproduction.

A major feature of Cayo Santiago is its geographic location in Puerto Rico. Situated in the Caribbean region, Cayo Santiago is subjected to extreme climatic events, such as hurricanes. The fact that three major hurricanes have directly affected the island of Cayo Santiago serves as a natural experiment to quantify the effects of these events on the demographic rates of a nonhuman primate population. This gives us insights into the potential effects of climate change and the predicted increased intensity of hurricanes on wild populations.

Today, we will estimate probability distributions of mean age at death in order to explore whether major hurricanes are important drivers of mortality in Cayo Santiago rhesus macaques. For this, we will use CSULB Quantitative Ecology Lab data from demographic studies lead by Dr. Raisa Hernández Pacheco on Cayo Santiago monkeys. In her study, Dr. Hernández Pacheco and colleagues used 45 years of data and evaluated annual survival and reproduction in order to determine if these vital rates changed during hurricane years (Fig. 1; Morcillo et al. 2020). So, let’s explore these changes using the distribution of age at death and probabilities to test whether mortality patterns change with the occurrence of an extreme climatic event.

Worked example

As we discussed in Chapter 2, we usually are not able to measure the entire population and get a true population parameter. We rely on a sampling process that reduces biases and increases measurement accuracy and precision to instead get a sample statistic, as seen in Chapter 2. Thus, we need to know how to infer a population parameter from sample data. To get started, let’s differentiate the population distribution and its parameter from the sampling distribution and its sample statistic:

  • population distribution - the whole set of values we are interested in. The population distribution is characterized by two parameters; the mean (\(\mu\)) and the standard deviation (\(\sigma\)).
  • parameter - a quantity describing the population.
  • sampling distribution - probability distribution of all values for a sample statistic we might obtain when sampling a population. This is, the pattern of sample means that will result as samples are drawn from the population. Here the sample mean \(\overline{y}\) and standard error s are the sample statistics characterizing the sampling distribution.
  • sample statistic - a quantity describing the sample.
  • probability distribution - a list of probabilities of all mutually exclusive outcomes of a random trial.
  • mutually exclusive events - two events that cannot occur a the same time.

Figure 2. Visual depiction of the population and sampling distributions. Say that we are interested in a monkey trait here represented by color. From this example, the mean population parameter should be close to the blue color. However, when samples are drawn from the population, a different sample statistics might result just by chance. Thus, the larger the sample size, the closer we can get to the population parameter.


1. Inferring population parameters from random samples

Let’s follow the monkey example, but let’s use real data this time. The Cayo Santiago rhesus macaque population processes an extraordinary demographic dataset that includes the age at which each female gave birth to an offspring. Let’s call that the “age at delivery”. Because we have data for all females in the population, we can plot the population distribution of age at delivery:


Figure 3. Frequency distribution of age at delivery in Cayo Santiago rhesus macaque females as counts (left panel) and as proportions (right panel).


The histograms above show the age at delivery of all females in the population alive during the period of 1984 to 2020 (n = 1,486). Because this is the population distribution, the relative frequency of age at delivery (Fig. 3, right panel) represents the probability of observing a female giving birth at that particular age when sampling a random female in the population. For example, if we sample a female giving birth from this population at random, there is about 9.5% chance she will have 5 years of age (Fig. 3).


From this population distribution we get the following population parameters (n = 1,486):


Name Parameter Value (age at delivery)
Mean μ 9.732
Standard deviation σ 4.482

However, we usually do not have the population distribution. Instead, we take a sample of the population and estimate a sampling distribution (Fig. 2). Let’s say we don’t have access to the demographic dataset of females at Cayo Santiago so we decide to go to Cayo Santiago and sample the population instead. Given constrains involving logistics, time and funding, we just sample 500 females at random out of the total 1,486 females in the population represented in Fig. 3. By doing this, we get the following sampling distribution:


Figure 4. Frequency distribution of age at delivery in Cayo Santiago rhesus macaque females from a random sample of n = 500 as counts (left panel) and as proportions (right panel).


By comparing the population distribution in Fig. 3 with the frequency distribution of the random sample in Fig. 4 (n = 500), we can see that they are not identical but they share some features. For example, both distributions indicate that most of the females have offspring at younger ages, relative to older ages.

From this sample distribution we get the following sample statistics (n = 500):

Name Statistic Sample value (age at delivery)
Mean ȳ 9.696
Standard deviation s 4.555

By estimating the mean age at delivery from a random sample of n = 500 females, we see that the sample statistics differ from the population parameters by chance. Given that 500 out of 1,486 females represents a good sample size for field work, our approximation to the true population parameter is good. However, sometimes we cannot yield large sample sizes and thus, our ability to describe population parameters is constrained.

Take the following example where we compare the population distribution to a random sample of n = 500 and n = 50 females:


Figure 5. Age at delivery of Cayo Santiago rhesus macaques females across samples.


2. The sampling distribution of ȳ

From the random sample n = 500, we estimated the sample statistic ȳ = 9.696 years. If we continue randomly sampling 500 females and estimating the sample statistic ȳ (as depicted in Fig. 2) we will get a probability distribution of the sample statistic ȳ, know as the sampling distribution.

With the help of a computer, we can easily draw 500 females randomly from our 1,486 female population 10,000 times and estimate the mean age at delivery ȳ for each of the 10,000 samples. The following histogram presents the frequency distribution of the 10,000 estimated ȳ:

From this sampling distribution of ȳ (n = 500), we can see that the sample statistic is a variable while the parameter of a population is a constant (9.717 years). For example, there is ~1% chance that the mean age at delivery estimated from a random sample of 500 females results in ~8.7 years, while there is a much higher chance that the mean age at delivery estimated from a random sample of 500 females results in 9 years. Thus, ȳ varies. From this sampling distribution, we can also see that the distribution of ȳ is centered on the true mean (\(\mu\)). Therefore, we say that ȳ is an accurate or unbiased estimate of (\(\mu\)).


3. Uncertainty of a sample statistic: the standard error

The standard deviation of a sampling distribution is called the standard error. The standard error serves as our measure of precision because it tells us the difference between the sample statistic and the population parameter. As we saw in Chapter 2, the smaller this difference - sampling error - the more precise our estimate is. As you may infer, the standard error decreases as the sample size increases. The formula for the standard error of ȳ is:


\(\sigma_\overline{Y}=\frac{\sigma}{\sqrt{n}}\)

For our example,
\(\sigma_\overline{Y}=\frac{4.480}{\sqrt{1486}}=0.116\)


However, if we do not have information about the true population parameters, we use s instead of \(\sigma\) in order to approximate the standard error of the mean by using the sample standard error. Let’s estimate it for our random sample (N = 500):
\(SE_\overline{Y}=\frac{s}{\sqrt{n}}\)

For our example,
\(SE_\overline{Y}=\frac{4.555}{\sqrt{1486}}=0.119\)


For our sample mean, we say that the age at delivery of females is 9.696±0.119 years (mean±SE).


Info-Box! When estimating with uncertainty, that is estimating from a sample, we need to report the precision of our sample statistic ȳ so that the reader has information of the sampling error. These results need to include the sample mean and standard error in the following format:


mean±SE


Note. We are interested in high precision (low SE) but keep in mind that our precision also depends on the type of data collected. In control seetings such as laboratories, we might expect relatively low SE. In uncontrolled settings such as nature, SE can be relatively higher as many variables can be working together to affect our data. Thus, the high need for large sample sizes to approach the true population parameter.


4. Probability distribution

We have use proportion and probability interchangeably (review Fig. 2). This is because the probability of an event is the proportion of times the event would occur if we repeat a random trial many times. Thus, the sampling distribution is a type of probability distribution; it gives us the proportion, or probability, of all values for a sample statistic. Here, values represent the different events and the sample represent the random trials.

As variables come in different types, so do probability distributions. Distributions can be discrete is they are describing a discrete variable. This is the case of all the age distributions describe with histograms above. Here age is taking discrete values. Distributions can also be continuous if they are describing the values a continuous variable can take. In this case, we use a curve whose height represents a probability density, rather than histograms. The probability density tells us the probability of obtaining a value within a certain range.

Let’s plot age at delivery for our random sample n = 500 females, using age as a continuous variable.


Figure 7. Probability density curve of age at delivery of Cayo Santiago rhesus macaque females (n = 500.


For our own interest, we can ignore the quantitative aspect of the y-axis of a probability density distribution, just focus on the shape and relative height of the curve. Rather than asking ourselves what is the probability that a female gives birth at age 15.2, for example, here we ask ourselves what is the probability that a female gives birth within the ages of say 15.2 to 17.1. This probability is the area under the curve between those x-axis values (in purple). Think about it, the probability of a particular age in a continuous probability density curve is almost 0 as age can take finite values. Thus, here we talk about ranges.


5. Probability of two or more events

The addition rule states that when two events are mutually exclusive, the probability of getting either of the two events is the sum of the probabilities of each of those events separately. For example, the probability of having a monkey offspring with black or grey hair, assuming these are mutually exclusive, is the sum of the probability of black hair and the probability of grey hair. This is intuitively and widely use in biology. However, we often are interested in more complex patterns. This involves combinations of events and thus, the multiplication of probabilities.

Say that we have the hypothesis that female offspring rhesus require more parental care, and thus they are more “energetically costly” than male offspring, specially for inexperienced females having their first and second offspring. Thus, we want to get insights into how many female undergo this burden early in life. For this, we want to estimate the probability that a female rhesus produces two daughters in a row during her first and second offspring deliveries. We can use probability trees.

According to our rhesus macaque data, 51.5% of offspring are females. Assuming the sex of consecutive offspring are independent events, there is a 0.515 probability to give birth to a daughter every single time a rhesus females is pregnant and 1-0.515 = 0.485 probability to give birth to a son. We follow assumptions of independence and the multiplication rule and build a probability tree:

Figure 8. Probability tree for all possible values of a female having two consecutive births.

From this tree, we can see that there is 26.5% chance of having two consecutive daughters, which challenges the original hypothesis. Of course, many more analyses and extra data is needed to actually answer the research question! But for now, let’s explore how we can infer other Cayo Santiago rhesus macaque demographic rates using these statistical tools!

Primate mortality in a tropical island


Death is invariably the final outcome of life. However, the rate at which individuals of a population die - mortality - varies across many population attributes such as sex and age and may be driven by many ecological factors. This produces the vast variation in life histories we observe in nature, where some individual die fast while others live longer. In her studies, Dr. Hernández Pacheco uses advance statistics and computational tools to describe the environmental factors driving Cayo Santiago rhesus macaque demographic rates. She has focused some analyses to understand the role of major hurricanes - a natural extreme disturbance in the tropics - in the Cayo Santiago rhesus macaque mortality patterns. B. The sampling distribution

From the random sample above (n = 737), we estimated a mean age at death \(\overline{y}=5.64\) years. Because there will always be some uncertainty in the sex variable (some individuals may die before sex can be identified), let’s estimate a sampling distribution using a random sample of n = 500 females. For this, we will employ the function sample() which allows us to sample a data frame at random. Because we want to repeat this process 10,000 times, we will use a loop in our coding. Loops are advance but don’t worry about them for this lab!

# defining an object to add the 10,000 sample statistics
r500 <- NULL 

# loop for sampling 500 females at random and estimate the mean age at death
for(i in 1:10000){
  temporarySample <- sample(floor(f$age_at_death), size = 500,
                                   replace = FALSE)
  r500[i] <- mean(temporarySample)
}

r500 <- as.data.frame(r500)

# viewing the new data frame created
View(r500)

# plotting the sampling distribution
p3 <- ggplot(r500,aes(x=r500)) +
  geom_histogram(aes(y=..count../sum(..count..)),binwidth = .1) +
  xlab("Female age at death (years)") +
  ylab("Probability")

p3

E. Probability of two or more events According to our analysis, a large proportion of females die early in life. In fact, we can estimate the age-specific probability of surviving from the age at death data. First, dying and surviving in a particular age are two mutually exclusive events; we either die or survive. Thus, if we know the probability of dying at a particular age, we can define the probability of not dying (i.e., surviving) at such age. We have all the information we need to estimate age-specific mortality. Let’s do that for the most vulnerable ages; from birth to 2 year of age.

# frequency table of age at death
table(floor(f$age_at_death))

# mortality during the first year of life
m0 <- 249/737
m0

# survival during the first year of life
s0 <- 1-m0
s0

# mortality during the second year of life
m1 <- 120/(737-249)
m1

# survival during the second year of life
s1 <- 1-m1
s1

# probability of surviving from birth to 2 years of age 
s0*s1

Here, we are calculating the probability of the survival sequence from birth (age = 0) to the second year of life (age = 2). Thus we need to estimate the probability that both events will occur. Because of this, we multiply each probability following the multiplication rule.
